WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:02.390 --> 00:00:05.640
GREG IVANOV: So sort of
the goal of this session

00:00:05.640 --> 00:00:08.670
is to get into the nitty
gritty, a little bit, of what it

00:00:08.670 --> 00:00:11.010
actually means to
develop for VR.

00:00:11.010 --> 00:00:14.580
So we've got a fascinating
selection of panelists

00:00:14.580 --> 00:00:17.430
to take us through some of the
foundational aspects of what

00:00:17.430 --> 00:00:20.070
it's like to actually
develop for VR.

00:00:20.070 --> 00:00:22.034
We've got Peter from
Resolution Games, who's

00:00:22.034 --> 00:00:24.450
going to talk about what it's
like to develop for a medium

00:00:24.450 --> 00:00:26.790
where a user has
no expectations.

00:00:26.790 --> 00:00:28.560
Bradley from BBC
is going to talk

00:00:28.560 --> 00:00:32.820
about transitioning the
brand and keeping the brand

00:00:32.820 --> 00:00:35.510
integrity into a new medium.

00:00:35.510 --> 00:00:37.620
And then Kay from
ARTE is going to talk

00:00:37.620 --> 00:00:42.110
about this
much-talked-about dichotomy

00:00:42.110 --> 00:00:46.830
or interrelation between linear
and interactive experiences.

00:00:46.830 --> 00:00:48.000
So come on up, guys.

00:00:51.332 --> 00:00:54.188
[APPLAUSE]

00:00:55.140 --> 00:00:59.040
And Peter, over to you
with the first lightning

00:00:59.040 --> 00:01:00.900
talk that you're going
to take us through.

00:01:04.209 --> 00:01:06.460
PETER STAHL: So I'm
going to look over there.

00:01:06.460 --> 00:01:07.270
OK.

00:01:07.270 --> 00:01:08.800
Hi, I'm Peter.

00:01:08.800 --> 00:01:11.650
And I work at Resolution Games.

00:01:11.650 --> 00:01:14.360
We're based in
Stockholm, Sweden.

00:01:14.360 --> 00:01:17.770
And when we develop games
in virtual reality now,

00:01:17.770 --> 00:01:22.480
we like to start in
reality, and then

00:01:22.480 --> 00:01:29.740
try to bring the things that
are interesting into fantastic.

00:01:29.740 --> 00:01:32.330
An example of that
is one of our games.

00:01:32.330 --> 00:01:34.330
We had the fortune as to
be one of the launching

00:01:34.330 --> 00:01:36.370
titles for Daydream.

00:01:36.370 --> 00:01:39.700
And it's called "Wonderglade."

00:01:39.700 --> 00:01:43.150
And it's basically
doing something

00:01:43.150 --> 00:01:47.170
familiar in an
unfamiliar context.

00:01:47.170 --> 00:01:49.450
So the example
from "Wonderglade,"

00:01:49.450 --> 00:01:52.570
that is that shooting hoops.

00:01:52.570 --> 00:01:55.450
Throwing a basketball
is very familiar.

00:01:55.450 --> 00:01:58.640
And you can't trick the brain.

00:01:58.640 --> 00:02:00.490
You've got to make
it feel like you're

00:02:00.490 --> 00:02:01.900
throwing that basketball.

00:02:01.900 --> 00:02:03.760
But you're doing it on the moon.

00:02:03.760 --> 00:02:05.470
That's kind of unfamiliar.

00:02:05.470 --> 00:02:07.972
So that's what we found
really interesting

00:02:07.972 --> 00:02:09.430
and what the players
like the most.

00:02:14.135 --> 00:02:15.010
GREG IVANOV: Awesome.

00:02:15.010 --> 00:02:17.065
Bradley?

00:02:17.065 --> 00:02:18.440
BRADLEY CROOKS:
Right, thank you.

00:02:18.440 --> 00:02:20.939
I'm Bradley from BBC Worldwide.

00:02:20.939 --> 00:02:23.230
So sometimes when a new kind
of technology comes along,

00:02:23.230 --> 00:02:25.104
it's really tempting to
kind of get caught up

00:02:25.104 --> 00:02:26.749
in what that technology
can do for you

00:02:26.749 --> 00:02:28.540
and maybe to forget
some of the things that

00:02:28.540 --> 00:02:30.230
make your brand what it is.

00:02:30.230 --> 00:02:32.230
And you should be thinking
about the things that

00:02:32.230 --> 00:02:33.810
make your brand what it is.

00:02:33.810 --> 00:02:35.560
And they might be as
practical as the kind

00:02:35.560 --> 00:02:37.840
of logos that you use or
the color schemes that you

00:02:37.840 --> 00:02:38.950
use and so on.

00:02:38.950 --> 00:02:40.979
But beyond that, there
should be other things

00:02:40.979 --> 00:02:43.270
in terms of kind of like the
brand value, so the things

00:02:43.270 --> 00:02:47.230
that represent your brand
at a very high level.

00:02:47.230 --> 00:02:49.750
And really, when you're
taking your brand

00:02:49.750 --> 00:02:51.790
into a new media
like VR, you need

00:02:51.790 --> 00:02:57.250
to be rigorously applying those
kind of checks and processes

00:02:57.250 --> 00:03:00.690
when you sort of take your
brand into a new medium.

00:03:00.690 --> 00:03:03.550
And to give you an example,
we're doing a lot of work

00:03:03.550 --> 00:03:05.380
at the moment with
our BBC Earth brand.

00:03:05.380 --> 00:03:07.164
It's natural history content.

00:03:07.164 --> 00:03:08.830
Some of you might be
familiar with this.

00:03:08.830 --> 00:03:10.246
One of the last
things that we did

00:03:10.246 --> 00:03:11.830
was called "Planet Earth 2."

00:03:11.830 --> 00:03:15.220
There's a scene in that where
there's iguanas versus snakes.

00:03:15.220 --> 00:03:17.092
We call these kind
of iconic scenes.

00:03:17.092 --> 00:03:19.300
And these are something that
we tend to have, always,

00:03:19.300 --> 00:03:22.060
when we put out
our kind of what we

00:03:22.060 --> 00:03:23.800
call landmark series each year.

00:03:23.800 --> 00:03:25.660
But really, this is
just underpinning

00:03:25.660 --> 00:03:27.670
the kind of brand
values that make up

00:03:27.670 --> 00:03:29.740
what BBC Earth is all about.

00:03:29.740 --> 00:03:31.990
Those brand values are
things like the editorial

00:03:31.990 --> 00:03:34.480
and scientific rigor.

00:03:34.480 --> 00:03:37.840
We make sure that everything
we do, in whatever medium,

00:03:37.840 --> 00:03:42.070
is rigorous in terms of its
application of the science

00:03:42.070 --> 00:03:43.960
that we apply.

00:03:43.960 --> 00:03:48.070
Probably the biggest
and most important

00:03:48.070 --> 00:03:49.630
thing is also storytelling.

00:03:49.630 --> 00:03:51.790
That's something in
everything that we do.

00:03:51.790 --> 00:03:55.930
And if you think about it, that
iguanas versus snakes example

00:03:55.930 --> 00:03:57.940
is a good example of
storytelling, right?

00:03:57.940 --> 00:03:59.500
And that's something that
we want to carry through

00:03:59.500 --> 00:04:01.666
into all of the media that
we do and all the content

00:04:01.666 --> 00:04:02.333
that we produce.

00:04:02.333 --> 00:04:04.416
So that's something that
we're thinking about when

00:04:04.416 --> 00:04:05.740
we're creating VR experiences.

00:04:05.740 --> 00:04:07.890
And finally, and
this is easy with VR,

00:04:07.890 --> 00:04:09.250
we're thinking about innovation.

00:04:09.250 --> 00:04:10.916
So that doesn't
necessarily come to mind

00:04:10.916 --> 00:04:13.270
when you're thinking about
BBC natural history content,

00:04:13.270 --> 00:04:15.565
but actually, every time
a new series comes out,

00:04:15.565 --> 00:04:16.690
we're using new technology.

00:04:16.690 --> 00:04:19.149
We're either using new
cameras or using drones

00:04:19.149 --> 00:04:22.330
to take pictures, or we're using
new submersible techniques.

00:04:22.330 --> 00:04:24.640
And again, we want to carry
through that kind of brand

00:04:24.640 --> 00:04:26.740
value into VR.

00:04:26.740 --> 00:04:29.247
So the types of things, the
types of kind of content

00:04:29.247 --> 00:04:31.580
that we're delivering, the
way in which people interact,

00:04:31.580 --> 00:04:35.252
and so on, we want
to innovate with.

00:04:35.252 --> 00:04:36.210
GREG IVANOV: Thank you.

00:04:36.210 --> 00:04:36.891
Kay?

00:04:36.891 --> 00:04:37.641
KAY MESEBERG: Yep.

00:04:40.499 --> 00:04:41.370
Yeah, that's me.

00:04:41.370 --> 00:04:43.960
Kay from ARTE.

00:04:43.960 --> 00:04:47.890
Our trigger for VR
at ARTE was really

00:04:47.890 --> 00:04:51.060
that it's something-- it's a
medium which attracts interest

00:04:51.060 --> 00:04:52.260
of all generations.

00:04:52.260 --> 00:04:54.330
I mean, from kids
to grandparents,

00:04:54.330 --> 00:04:58.880
everybody is attracted by VR
and is fascinated by that.

00:04:58.880 --> 00:05:04.580
But to get and to keep this
interest for VR productions--

00:05:04.580 --> 00:05:09.390
we started now in 2014, I
think, with the first one--

00:05:09.390 --> 00:05:11.760
a key question is
really the interface

00:05:11.760 --> 00:05:12.870
and the accessibility.

00:05:12.870 --> 00:05:17.580
So interacting in VR should
be close to human behavior,

00:05:17.580 --> 00:05:19.450
as easy as breathing
or drinking water.

00:05:19.450 --> 00:05:24.930
It should be really easy
to seamlessly get into VR,

00:05:24.930 --> 00:05:28.740
and also the same for augmented
reality for some projects

00:05:28.740 --> 00:05:30.300
we're working on.

00:05:30.300 --> 00:05:34.540
I would like to show you two
examples how we distinguish

00:05:34.540 --> 00:05:35.790
the things a bit.

00:05:35.790 --> 00:05:39.660
I mean, one is that we do a lot
more linear productions based

00:05:39.660 --> 00:05:45.570
on 360 video, but also added
with metadata, which as,

00:05:45.570 --> 00:05:47.170
for instance, "Dolphin
Man," a series,

00:05:47.170 --> 00:05:49.450
a VR series we just published.

00:05:49.450 --> 00:05:51.750
So we take people to
exceptional places

00:05:51.750 --> 00:05:54.270
and to give access to
exceptional places.

00:05:54.270 --> 00:05:55.810
In this example,
you can really dive

00:05:55.810 --> 00:05:59.700
with free divers, more than
five meters, 10, 20 meters,

00:05:59.700 --> 00:06:01.590
50 meters down in the ocean.

00:06:01.590 --> 00:06:03.090
You can swim with
dolphins and stuff

00:06:03.090 --> 00:06:04.541
like that, and sperm whales.

00:06:04.541 --> 00:06:05.790
So it's something exceptional.

00:06:05.790 --> 00:06:08.910
You cannot live like
that out of the box.

00:06:08.910 --> 00:06:12.360
And the second one is more
interactive experiences,

00:06:12.360 --> 00:06:16.350
but also with the same
goal to be really seamless

00:06:16.350 --> 00:06:17.580
in terms of navigation.

00:06:17.580 --> 00:06:18.820
That's "Notes On Blindness."

00:06:18.820 --> 00:06:21.720
Its a story of a British
man who lost sight,

00:06:21.720 --> 00:06:23.580
and he did an audio
journal about it.

00:06:23.580 --> 00:06:25.650
And the fascinating thing
with this audio journal

00:06:25.650 --> 00:06:30.660
is that it really explains
extremely interesting what

00:06:30.660 --> 00:06:32.050
happens to him.

00:06:32.050 --> 00:06:36.280
So we did a VR experience with
our French partners about it.

00:06:36.280 --> 00:06:37.530
And its extremely interesting.

00:06:37.530 --> 00:06:43.680
After you saw it, you understand
what it means to lose sight.

00:06:43.680 --> 00:06:45.930
And the interactive
part in that is just

00:06:45.930 --> 00:06:49.811
based on the way you move, with
sound, with different things

00:06:49.811 --> 00:06:50.310
like that.

00:06:50.310 --> 00:06:52.770
You don't need to click
on something or anything.

00:06:52.770 --> 00:06:56.650
Its just seamless into
the whole experience.

00:06:56.650 --> 00:06:59.760
So these are the goals
we are working on.

00:06:59.760 --> 00:07:01.286
And we're working on more in VR.

00:07:01.286 --> 00:07:02.036
GREG IVANOV: Cool.

00:07:02.036 --> 00:07:03.290
Thank you.

00:07:03.290 --> 00:07:06.930
So super amazing to have
such a wide cross-section

00:07:06.930 --> 00:07:08.810
of developers in the room.

00:07:08.810 --> 00:07:11.400
And I think probably, let's
make this practical, right?

00:07:11.400 --> 00:07:14.250
So we've got developers
here who are perhaps

00:07:14.250 --> 00:07:16.980
thinking of getting into VR.

00:07:16.980 --> 00:07:20.160
And with that, you know,
what would be the number one

00:07:20.160 --> 00:07:22.950
piece of advice that you'd
give to someone who is thinking

00:07:22.950 --> 00:07:25.740
of starting out in VR today?

00:07:25.740 --> 00:07:28.730
Bradley, what would you say?

00:07:28.730 --> 00:07:30.900
BRADLEY CROOKS: It's
a good question.

00:07:30.900 --> 00:07:34.530
I think, and I've always sort
of said, go in with your eyes

00:07:34.530 --> 00:07:35.840
open.

00:07:35.840 --> 00:07:37.392
Quite literally, maybe.

00:07:37.392 --> 00:07:41.760
You know, it's not an
easy kind of medium

00:07:41.760 --> 00:07:43.680
to develop for it first.

00:07:43.680 --> 00:07:46.530
There's quite a
steep learning curve.

00:07:46.530 --> 00:07:49.170
Our first foray
into it, we sort of

00:07:49.170 --> 00:07:50.960
thought, oh, this will
be relatively easy.

00:07:50.960 --> 00:07:54.720
We'll sort of crack a couple
of experiences out there

00:07:54.720 --> 00:07:56.970
and get them through submission.

00:07:56.970 --> 00:07:59.380
And everything took
three times as long,

00:07:59.380 --> 00:08:01.587
cost three times as much,
as we were expecting.

00:08:01.587 --> 00:08:03.420
And actually, to kind
of go back to my point

00:08:03.420 --> 00:08:05.430
I was making before, to
uphold the things that

00:08:05.430 --> 00:08:07.230
are important to us
about our brands,

00:08:07.230 --> 00:08:09.620
like the quality of
the output and so on,

00:08:09.620 --> 00:08:11.839
actually took a
significant amount of time.

00:08:11.839 --> 00:08:13.380
And I think it's
only really just now

00:08:13.380 --> 00:08:15.780
that we've really
kind of learned

00:08:15.780 --> 00:08:19.480
how to approach that
properly and, you know,

00:08:19.480 --> 00:08:20.900
do things in the right way.

00:08:20.900 --> 00:08:23.450
And that will be a sort of
continuing learning process

00:08:23.450 --> 00:08:25.690
as new tech comes out and so on.

00:08:25.690 --> 00:08:27.930
GREG IVANOV: So what
would you say, then,

00:08:27.930 --> 00:08:30.590
in that sense to someone's who's
just thinking of starting out?

00:08:30.590 --> 00:08:35.520
Or any of you guys that
have a good piece of wisdom

00:08:35.520 --> 00:08:37.526
in terms of the first
thing to think about

00:08:37.526 --> 00:08:39.150
or the first potential
failure that you

00:08:39.150 --> 00:08:44.790
have to think about in
terms of developing for VR?

00:08:44.790 --> 00:08:47.520
PETER STAHL: I would
say, start with the core.

00:08:47.520 --> 00:08:48.625
Start simple.

00:08:48.625 --> 00:08:51.000
One of my developers usually
says, throw crap on the wall

00:08:51.000 --> 00:08:53.380
and see what sticks.

00:08:53.380 --> 00:08:54.180
You've got to try.

00:08:54.180 --> 00:08:56.040
You've got to try
a lot of things,

00:08:56.040 --> 00:08:57.400
because it's a moving platform.

00:08:57.400 --> 00:08:59.425
It's a moving target
that you're aiming for.

00:08:59.425 --> 00:09:01.200
So you just try, try, try, try.

00:09:01.200 --> 00:09:04.436
And come back to the things
that just feels good.

00:09:04.436 --> 00:09:06.810
BRADLEY CROOKS: I think knowing
what your objectives are.

00:09:06.810 --> 00:09:08.270
You know, you have an end goal.

00:09:08.270 --> 00:09:10.714
What are you actually
trying to achieve with this?

00:09:10.714 --> 00:09:13.130
Are you trying to do this from
a commercial point of view?

00:09:13.130 --> 00:09:15.349
Are you trying to do it
from a brand point of view?

00:09:15.349 --> 00:09:16.390
What are your objectives?

00:09:16.390 --> 00:09:17.940
And that's probably true
of most ventures, right?

00:09:17.940 --> 00:09:20.100
But I think it's particularly
true with something

00:09:20.100 --> 00:09:23.270
which combines a lot of
creativity and a lot of tech.

00:09:23.270 --> 00:09:25.620
So it is, like you say, it's
kind of a moving target.

00:09:25.620 --> 00:09:28.200
And you know, sometimes
it moves whilst you're

00:09:28.200 --> 00:09:29.500
developing for it, right?

00:09:29.500 --> 00:09:31.290
So yeah, I mean, I
think it's good to have

00:09:31.290 --> 00:09:32.190
an end goal in mind.

00:09:32.190 --> 00:09:34.950
KAY MESEBERG: I think
it's also extremely

00:09:34.950 --> 00:09:39.120
interesting and important
to work on ideas, in the way

00:09:39.120 --> 00:09:41.980
that you have an idea, and you
can put it in one sentence,

00:09:41.980 --> 00:09:44.620
and you pitch to someone,
and it makes click.

00:09:44.620 --> 00:09:47.830
And I think that's a key
factor in the beginning.

00:09:47.830 --> 00:09:49.510
And then you add the tech to it.

00:09:49.510 --> 00:09:51.410
But if you have this
kind of basic idea

00:09:51.410 --> 00:09:54.250
which really convince
people, and it convince,

00:09:54.250 --> 00:09:57.640
you know, a little boy of
five years or a granny of 90,

00:09:57.640 --> 00:09:59.560
then you think you know
that you are really

00:09:59.560 --> 00:10:01.840
working on something
interesting and great

00:10:01.840 --> 00:10:03.200
and which can be really great.

00:10:03.200 --> 00:10:04.283
And then you add the tech.

00:10:04.283 --> 00:10:08.721
You add the different ways of
sound, of cameras, of unity,

00:10:08.721 --> 00:10:09.220
whatever.

00:10:09.220 --> 00:10:11.200
You decide what you
want to use for it.

00:10:11.200 --> 00:10:14.167
And that's, I
think, a key factor.

00:10:14.167 --> 00:10:15.250
GREG IVANOV: That's great.

00:10:15.250 --> 00:10:17.170
I think one interesting
mantra that we all

00:10:17.170 --> 00:10:20.939
know in a mobile world is
fail cheap and fail fast.

00:10:20.939 --> 00:10:22.480
And I just want to
kind of drill down

00:10:22.480 --> 00:10:24.400
on that a little bit
in the context of this

00:10:24.400 --> 00:10:26.306
question as well.

00:10:26.306 --> 00:10:27.930
It kind of works in
mobile pretty well.

00:10:27.930 --> 00:10:31.750
You can fail cheap
and fail fast.

00:10:31.750 --> 00:10:35.290
With VR and the costs and
the know-how associated

00:10:35.290 --> 00:10:39.610
with developing for VR, that's
presumably a lot harder to do.

00:10:39.610 --> 00:10:41.080
So how do you--

00:10:41.080 --> 00:10:43.360
do you still apply
the same method?

00:10:43.360 --> 00:10:46.630
Or do you just not, and you
see this as an investment

00:10:46.630 --> 00:10:47.710
of a different kind?

00:10:47.710 --> 00:10:49.900
And you have to
convince, perhaps,

00:10:49.900 --> 00:10:53.230
your leadership that this is
just the way it has to be?

00:10:53.230 --> 00:10:55.072
Peter, do you have
a take on that?

00:10:55.072 --> 00:10:57.530
PETER STAHL: Yeah, I guess they
must throw crap on the wall

00:10:57.530 --> 00:11:00.430
and see what sticks.

00:11:00.430 --> 00:11:03.260
Yeah, it does apply,
I think, partially.

00:11:03.260 --> 00:11:05.405
I think you have
to make a few bets.

00:11:05.405 --> 00:11:07.780
I think you've got to pick a
few things that you actually

00:11:07.780 --> 00:11:09.850
believe is going to happen.

00:11:09.850 --> 00:11:12.550
Like for example, we
believe that the cords in VR

00:11:12.550 --> 00:11:14.110
are going to go away.

00:11:14.110 --> 00:11:16.000
You're going to be
moving around a lot more.

00:11:16.000 --> 00:11:17.541
There's a lot of
those examples where

00:11:17.541 --> 00:11:21.400
you got to go, that we really
believe is going to happen,

00:11:21.400 --> 00:11:25.000
because, again, it's
a moving platform.

00:11:25.000 --> 00:11:28.690
It does apply in the
sense that if you've

00:11:28.690 --> 00:11:30.600
got to do something
that you are very

00:11:30.600 --> 00:11:35.620
unsure of if it's going to be
successful or not, then yeah.

00:11:35.620 --> 00:11:36.692
Fail fast.

00:11:36.692 --> 00:11:38.650
KAY MESEBERG: I think
it's also important to be

00:11:38.650 --> 00:11:40.870
flexible in a way
that you can port

00:11:40.870 --> 00:11:43.150
your experience with
different other platforms,

00:11:43.150 --> 00:11:47.090
to do real life experiences in
cinemas, to bring it on mobile,

00:11:47.090 --> 00:11:49.810
to bring it on different
headsets and stuff like that.

00:11:49.810 --> 00:11:52.810
I mean, that can really
trigger the evolution.

00:11:52.810 --> 00:11:54.880
And it can help
that with porting,

00:11:54.880 --> 00:11:57.880
you redefine the
things you're doing.

00:11:57.880 --> 00:12:00.010
So I think it's
really amazing to see

00:12:00.010 --> 00:12:05.300
that things are working great on
Daydream, but also on Android.

00:12:05.300 --> 00:12:08.245
But on Android, they are known
as, also, some other headsets

00:12:08.245 --> 00:12:09.520
and stuff like that.

00:12:09.520 --> 00:12:11.770
But still, we can show
it in planetariums,

00:12:11.770 --> 00:12:15.430
in screens which
are 30 meters large.

00:12:15.430 --> 00:12:18.490
And you can watch it
together with 300 people

00:12:18.490 --> 00:12:20.350
in a cinema-like setting.

00:12:20.350 --> 00:12:23.480
So I think that's really
the interesting, great thing

00:12:23.480 --> 00:12:28.570
with VR today, that you are
on a step into something new,

00:12:28.570 --> 00:12:29.770
and everybody's trying out.

00:12:29.770 --> 00:12:32.890
And then as many as
different ways you try out,

00:12:32.890 --> 00:12:36.694
and I think you will succeed
in the one or the other.

00:12:36.694 --> 00:12:38.110
GREG IVANOV: By
