00:13:14.940 --> 00:13:19.620
to have the passive watching
of the videos in 360

00:13:19.620 --> 00:13:22.560
or virtual reality content
comparing to active.

00:13:22.560 --> 00:13:26.440
So what is your point of
view of to bring more--

00:13:26.440 --> 00:13:32.660
if it's the way to bring more
active interaction with video,

00:13:32.660 --> 00:13:33.870
or--?

00:13:33.870 --> 00:13:40.050
We are now in Android platform,
with a new generation on Oculus

00:13:40.050 --> 00:13:41.620
will be ready in a few weeks.

00:13:41.620 --> 00:13:43.980
And then, we have some
[INAUDIBLE] VR [INAUDIBLE]

00:13:43.980 --> 00:13:45.040
in our own channel.

00:13:45.040 --> 00:13:47.040
So what is your
approach to bring

00:13:47.040 --> 00:13:52.120
more customers [INAUDIBLE]
to show this, see the content

00:13:52.120 --> 00:13:53.990
and to be entertained
by the content,

00:13:53.990 --> 00:13:58.680
or to go more to interact
with the content in VR world?

00:13:58.680 --> 00:14:00.277
Thank you.

00:14:00.277 --> 00:14:02.110
BRADLEY CROOKS: Yeah,
I mean, I think that--

00:14:02.110 --> 00:14:04.427
it's an interesting question,
because different parts

00:14:04.427 --> 00:14:06.010
of the BBC are doing
different things.

00:14:06.010 --> 00:14:07.185
We're doing kind of--

00:14:07.185 --> 00:14:09.310
people who are interested
in sort of live streaming

00:14:09.310 --> 00:14:12.370
e-sports through VR and so on.

00:14:12.370 --> 00:14:15.250
There's a big divide, I
think, between 360 content

00:14:15.250 --> 00:14:16.430
and real-time content.

00:14:16.430 --> 00:14:18.430
And you know, obviously
there's a certain amount

00:14:18.430 --> 00:14:20.560
that you can do to
overlay one or the other.

00:14:20.560 --> 00:14:22.390
I think in everything
you create, again,

00:14:22.390 --> 00:14:24.160
thinking of what
the end goal is,

00:14:24.160 --> 00:14:25.570
you need to be adding value.

00:14:25.570 --> 00:14:28.700
And I think one of the
problems that VR has had is--

00:14:28.700 --> 00:14:31.420
and it's the same with most kind
of new techs-- is people go,

00:14:31.420 --> 00:14:32.920
wow, there's this
amazing new thing.

00:14:32.920 --> 00:14:34.855
Let's build some stuff for it.

00:14:34.855 --> 00:14:36.730
Not necessarily thinking
if this is something

00:14:36.730 --> 00:14:38.230
that the audience
actually wants.

00:14:38.230 --> 00:14:40.355
And I think you have to be
thinking, in any product

00:14:40.355 --> 00:14:43.150
development, you know,
who's my audience?

00:14:43.150 --> 00:14:45.610
What do they need?

00:14:45.610 --> 00:14:46.720
And what can I offer them?

00:14:46.720 --> 00:14:48.630
And if you can answer
those three things,

00:14:48.630 --> 00:14:50.830
and that allows you to come
up with a product which

00:14:50.830 --> 00:14:53.380
is going to make their life
easier or more entertaining

00:14:53.380 --> 00:14:55.850
or whatever it is, then I
think you'll be successful.

00:14:55.850 --> 00:14:57.683
But I think just doing
something because you

00:14:57.683 --> 00:15:00.400
hope the market will develop,
I think that's risky.

00:15:00.400 --> 00:15:01.430
Very risky.

00:15:01.430 --> 00:15:05.705
So I think it's really key to
be thinking of your consumer

00:15:05.705 --> 00:15:09.010
always, what's going
to be good for them.

00:15:09.010 --> 00:15:11.800
If that answers your question.

00:15:11.800 --> 00:15:15.390
GREG IVANOV: Kay, you probably
have a point of view on that,

00:15:15.390 --> 00:15:21.150
since you spoke about
linear and interactive.

00:15:21.150 --> 00:15:25.120
KAY MESEBERG: I think the
real interactive is still

00:15:25.120 --> 00:15:25.940
based on mobile.

00:15:25.940 --> 00:15:27.580
It's based on the VR headsets.

00:15:27.580 --> 00:15:32.547
And we see grow, that there
are more and more headsets

00:15:32.547 --> 00:15:33.130
on the market.

00:15:33.130 --> 00:15:36.830
So the market is getting
bigger and bigger.

00:15:36.830 --> 00:15:42.100
Still, with linear,
you have the advantage

00:15:42.100 --> 00:15:46.420
that you can really
make access to people

00:15:46.420 --> 00:15:49.480
who don't have a
headset but who are

00:15:49.480 --> 00:15:51.040
familiar with video in general.

00:15:51.040 --> 00:15:53.830
So they understand it like that.

00:15:53.830 --> 00:15:59.620
And I think if you create out
of that great experiences, that

00:15:59.620 --> 00:16:02.050
can be a bit more
convincing just

00:16:02.050 --> 00:16:06.010
to understand this
new evolutionary step

00:16:06.010 --> 00:16:10.930
into computing and this kind
of new platform, this kind

00:16:10.930 --> 00:16:15.870
of new interactive
realities coming up there.

00:16:15.870 --> 00:16:18.970
And it's a really good
tool, like a technology

00:16:18.970 --> 00:16:21.730
that's kind of doing the
bridge between the two.

00:16:21.730 --> 00:16:24.100
And that's why we
shouldn't underestimate,

00:16:24.100 --> 00:16:26.945
really, linear-based videos.

00:16:26.945 --> 00:16:30.420
GREG IVANOV: Yeah, and I think,
[INAUDIBLE] from the Daydream

00:16:30.420 --> 00:16:34.030
side, we've seen that actually
the most-used app on Daydream

00:16:34.030 --> 00:16:35.080
was YouTube.

00:16:35.080 --> 00:16:40.210
So linear 360 video
is playing a big part.

00:16:40.210 --> 00:16:45.340
And I don't think we want to
say that 360 or linear video

00:16:45.340 --> 00:16:48.490
is some kind of a step towards
the ultimate goal, which

00:16:48.490 --> 00:16:49.270
is interactive.

00:16:49.270 --> 00:16:49.930
It's not.

00:16:49.930 --> 00:16:52.739
I think, as Bradley
mentioned, it's

00:16:52.739 --> 00:16:54.530
really about what you're
trying to achieve.

00:16:54.530 --> 00:16:58.940
And sometimes 360 video is
exactly the right format.

00:16:58.940 --> 00:17:01.770
And also, it's often
cheaper to produce.

00:17:01.770 --> 00:17:03.610
So that's a good thing, too.

00:17:03.610 --> 00:17:06.440
I think there was another
question from a gentleman here?

00:17:10.060 --> 00:17:11.020
AUDIENCE: Hi, hello.

00:17:11.020 --> 00:17:11.520
I'm Antoine.

00:17:11.520 --> 00:17:12.436
I work at [INAUDIBLE].

00:17:12.436 --> 00:17:13.800
We're a language learning app.

00:17:13.800 --> 00:17:18.660
And we've just built
a VR experience

00:17:18.660 --> 00:17:20.010
for another platform.

00:17:20.010 --> 00:17:24.630
And one of my questions
is around replayability,

00:17:24.630 --> 00:17:29.300
because obviously, those
experiences are quite finite.

00:17:29.300 --> 00:17:32.880
And I guess, as all
platforms, we'll

00:17:32.880 --> 00:17:35.270
be looking at retention
as a key metric.

00:17:35.270 --> 00:17:37.890
So how do you make
sure, you know,

00:17:37.890 --> 00:17:39.930
that the headset
just doesn't become

00:17:39.930 --> 00:17:44.130
one thing that's just left
in the cupboards out of view,

00:17:44.130 --> 00:17:46.560
and people come back to
your experiences over time?

00:17:50.577 --> 00:17:52.160
PETER STAHL: I would
start by saying--

00:17:52.160 --> 00:17:52.660
sorry.

00:17:55.440 --> 00:17:59.540
As I said, placing bets
before in what you believe

00:17:59.540 --> 00:18:02.810
will happen in time to come.

00:18:02.810 --> 00:18:05.610
I personally believe that
we're not quite there yet.

00:18:05.610 --> 00:18:07.160
There's a cap.

00:18:07.160 --> 00:18:10.340
There's an experience
cap, which is--

00:18:10.340 --> 00:18:12.850
that's sad, but
it's going to come.

00:18:12.850 --> 00:18:15.800
Technology is moving
extremely fast.

00:18:15.800 --> 00:18:27.240
And I think, yeah, you've got to
be there when it goes relevant.

00:18:27.240 --> 00:18:31.250
I think you've got to be ready
when putting that thing on

00:18:31.250 --> 00:18:36.470
and whatever happens in that
reality feels relevant to you.

00:18:36.470 --> 00:18:38.210
And also, you've got
to place those bets

00:18:38.210 --> 00:18:42.870
on what you believe is relevant
to your target audience.

00:18:42.870 --> 00:18:46.910
For example, a group
of young people

00:18:46.910 --> 00:18:52.290
might want to meet up and
play their favorite game

00:18:52.290 --> 00:18:53.030
and so forth.

00:18:53.030 --> 00:18:56.900
And you might want to meet
with your son or your daughter

00:18:56.900 --> 00:18:58.820
across the world.

00:18:58.820 --> 00:19:02.059
Different groups.

00:19:02.059 --> 00:19:03.600
BRADLEY CROOKS:
Yeah, I mean, there's

00:19:03.600 --> 00:19:07.020
some BBC research, actually,
that was done recently

00:19:07.020 --> 00:19:08.580
about little kind of barriers.

00:19:08.580 --> 00:19:09.540
You might have seen it.

00:19:09.540 --> 00:19:10.450
It's really interesting.

00:19:10.450 --> 00:19:12.366
And one of the biggest
barriers is that people

00:19:12.366 --> 00:19:13.620
lose their headsets.

00:19:13.620 --> 00:19:16.800
So you know, it's
a different thing

00:19:16.800 --> 00:19:21.360
to kind of switch on your TV and
interact with content that way,

00:19:21.360 --> 00:19:23.010
to actually go and
find your headset,

00:19:23.010 --> 00:19:26.190
put it on, go through the
process of booting it up,

00:19:26.190 --> 00:19:26.820
and so on.

00:19:26.820 --> 00:19:28.320
And the research
found that that was

00:19:28.320 --> 00:19:30.069
one of the most difficult
things about VR,

00:19:30.069 --> 00:19:33.990
is that people tend to do things
in order of how easy they are.

00:19:33.990 --> 00:19:36.990
And VR comes fairly
low down the list.

00:19:36.990 --> 00:19:38.490
And that's one
reason why I think it

00:19:38.490 --> 00:19:40.800
has to have that added value.

00:19:40.800 --> 00:19:42.960
You know, it has to be
something that people

00:19:42.960 --> 00:19:45.145
are going to kind of want
as a destination to go to.

00:19:45.145 --> 00:19:47.520
But I do think, as well-- we
were just talking about this

00:19:47.520 --> 00:19:48.380
before--

00:19:48.380 --> 00:19:50.790
that we are in the really
early stages of VR.

00:19:50.790 --> 00:19:52.666
There's been a huge
amount of noise about it.

00:19:52.666 --> 00:19:54.581
And people are saying,
it's not going to work,

00:19:54.581 --> 00:19:56.580
and people aren't
investing in it and so on.

00:19:56.580 --> 00:19:58.288
It's incredibly unfair,
because it's only

00:19:58.288 --> 00:20:01.320
really been in its current form
around for 18 months to two

00:20:01.320 --> 00:20:02.050
years.

00:20:02.050 --> 00:20:04.341
If you look at the mobile
market, which has been around

00:20:04.341 --> 00:20:07.650
for a long, long time,
much of the sophistication

00:20:07.650 --> 00:20:09.990
about retention and
so on is only really

00:20:09.990 --> 00:20:12.107
now kind of coming to the fore.

00:20:12.107 --> 00:20:14.190
And you look at the way
that mobile companies sort

00:20:14.190 --> 00:20:18.720
of reengage people and
so on, that's years

00:20:18.720 --> 00:20:22.870
of R&amp;D and investment and tying
into social channels and so on.

00:20:22.870 --> 00:20:26.176
And I think VR and AR will
have that eventually as well.

00:20:26.176 --> 00:20:28.050
And that will help with
retention and getting

00:20:28.050 --> 00:20:29.800
people to come back
in and discoverability

00:20:29.800 --> 00:20:30.857
and all those things.

00:20:30.857 --> 00:20:32.940
KAY MESEBERG: Yeah, it's
an interesting comparison

00:20:32.940 --> 00:20:35.760
to mobile, because,
actually, the first mobile

00:20:35.760 --> 00:20:38.270
or smartphones, they came to
market in the '90s, something

00:20:38.270 --> 00:20:39.130
like that.

00:20:39.130 --> 00:20:43.290
But it made boom in the
2000s, with Android,

00:20:43.290 --> 00:20:44.670
with iOS and stuff like that.

00:20:44.670 --> 00:20:50.150
So there was quite a big period
In between the first market

00:20:50.150 --> 00:20:53.305
phones, like the Nokia back in
the days and stuff like that.

00:20:53.305 --> 00:20:59.160
And I think that seeing VR
moving today, since, like,

00:20:59.160 --> 00:21:02.870
2014, since we do
it, it's really fast.

00:21:02.870 --> 00:21:06.990
I think I'm quite surprised
in different levels,

00:21:06.990 --> 00:21:09.550
I mean, in adoption
and stuff like that.

00:21:09.550 --> 00:21:14.100
But I think, also, that the
midterm or the next goal

00:21:14.100 --> 00:21:19.650
will be that it's kind of
something which is where people

00:21:19.650 --> 00:21:21.690
ask for experiences,
but not because it's

00:21:21.690 --> 00:21:24.960
VR, because they ask that they
heard something is really great

00:21:24.960 --> 00:21:27.040
and they want to play it,
or they want to see it,

00:21:27.040 --> 00:21:27.780
or whatever.

00:21:27.780 --> 00:21:31.342
I think that will be the
next goal for the next year.

00:21:31.342 --> 00:21:33.510
GREG IVANOV: Yeah, I think
that, to your question

00:21:33.510 --> 00:21:36.600
around replayability,
there's kind of, I think,

00:21:36.600 --> 00:21:38.820
three things that need
to happen and align

00:21:38.820 --> 00:21:41.790
in a certain way, which
is hardware, software,

00:21:41.790 --> 00:21:42.870
and content, right?

00:21:42.870 --> 00:21:46.039
So if it becomes the barrier to
experiencing VR is a lot lower,

00:21:46.039 --> 00:21:48.330
then replayability is not
really that much of an issue,

00:21:48.330 --> 00:21:50.910
because you can just pick
this thing up, and it's cheap,

00:21:50.910 --> 00:21:53.820
and it's easy, right?

00:21:53.820 --> 00:21:57.660
And I think to follow on with
this, one interesting stat

00:21:57.660 --> 00:22:01.920
that I guess you guys know
is that Goldman Sachs says

00:22:01.920 --> 00:22:06.180
by 2025, VR will become
an $80 billion industry,

00:22:06.180 --> 00:22:09.210
taking over TV.

00:22:09.210 --> 00:22:12.770
That's interesting.

00:22:12.770 --> 00:22:17.130
So be that as it may,
what do you think

00:22:17.130 --> 00:22:21.630
are the key steps that need
to happen in order for VR

00:22:21.630 --> 00:22:25.652
to go mainstream,
whatever that means?

00:22:25.652 --> 00:22:30.180
KAY MESEBERG: I think if you
look back on smartphone market,

00:22:30.180 --> 00:22:32.130
I mean, today you
have a phenomenon

00:22:32.130 --> 00:22:34.890
that people say they
talked to someone,

00:22:34.890 --> 00:22:35.850
but you don't know how.

00:22:35.850 --> 00:22:37.110
I mean, did they call them?

00:22:37.110 --> 00:22:39.750
Did they write a
WhatsApp, whatever?

00:22:39.750 --> 00:22:40.980
You know, you don't know.

00:22:40.980 --> 00:22:43.420
They just say that they are
in communication with someone.

00:22:43.420 --> 00:22:48.510
And I think VR should be, and
AR should be, at the same level,

00:22:48.510 --> 00:22:52.740
more or less, that
it's used intuitively.

00:22:52.740 --> 00:22:53.825
Like, OK, it's there.

00:22:53.825 --> 00:22:54.450
It's something.

00:22:54.450 --> 00:22:58.244
And I do a call with my
friends in the states in 360,

00:22:58.244 --> 00:23:00.660
and I see where they are, and
we can share the environment

00:23:00.660 --> 00:23:01.493
and stuff like that.

00:23:01.493 --> 00:23:03.540
So all this, I think, will come.

00:23:03.540 --> 00:23:07.680
But you know, I think this
will be more or less the kind

00:23:07.680 --> 00:23:12.120
of level where it will arrive.

00:23:12.120 --> 00:23:14.440
BRADLEY CROOKS:
Yeah, I mean, I think

00:23:14.440 --> 00:23:16.120
there's an interesting
kind of adoption

00:23:16.120 --> 00:23:20.145
curve with any new technology,
that it has to become sort of--

00:23:20.145 --> 00:23:21.540
it has to be
accessible to people

00:23:21.540 --> 00:23:23.550
and sort of be something that
people are familiar with.

00:23:23.550 --> 00:23:25.680
And obviously, as a
younger generation grows up

00:23:25.680 --> 00:23:28.290
with that tech, they'll
probably be more willing to kind

00:23:28.290 --> 00:23:30.859
of put headsets on and so on.

00:23:30.859 --> 00:23:32.400
But again, I think
it just comes down

00:23:32.400 --> 00:23:34.836
to what are the
applications going to be?

00:23:34.836 --> 00:23:36.210
And I think you'll
probably begin

00:23:36.210 --> 00:23:40.367
to see VR finding
different areas which

00:23:40.367 --> 00:23:41.200
it's really good at.

00:23:41.200 --> 00:23:43.140
So I think it has
lots of applications

00:23:43.140 --> 00:23:45.730
for business to
business and training

00:23:45.730 --> 00:23:46.770
and that type of thing.

00:23:46.770 --> 00:23:50.914
I think there'll be a lot more
installation-based VR coming up

00:23:50.914 --> 00:23:52.080
in the next couple of years.

00:23:52.080 --> 00:23:53.820
You know, you'll see
it at theme parks.

00:23:53.820 --> 00:23:56.040
You'll see it in malls
and things like that.

00:23:56.040 --> 00:23:58.890
And I think that, again, will
kind of give the general public

00:23:58.890 --> 00:23:59.932
